    <h2>Bankroll Rules for Real Money Play</h2>
    <p>
      Real money play requires discipline. The most common mistake new players make is betting too large relative to their session bankroll. Here are the ground rules:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Session budget</strong>: Only deposit what you are comfortable losing in one session. Never play with rent money or funds you cannot afford to lose.</li>
      <li><strong>Bet sizing</strong>: Keep each round's total bet at 1–2% of your session budget. A $100 session budget means $1–$2 per round maximum.</li>
      <li><strong>Stop-loss</strong>: Decide your exit point before starting. If your balance drops 30–40% from your starting amount, end the session.</li>
      <li><strong>Take-profit</strong>: Set a win target too. If you hit 2× your starting balance, seriously consider stopping — variance works both ways.</li>
      <li><strong>No chasing</strong>: If you hit your stop-loss, stop completely. Reloading mid-session to chase losses is the fastest route to a large loss.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Use our <a href="/session-planner">session planner tool</a> to set all of these rules before you open the game. Having them written down makes them much easier to follow under pressure.
    </p>

